<F P=100> ARAB AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Egypt </F>
<H3> <TI>   Interior Minister on `Foreign Quarters' Involvement </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC1103104194 Cairo MENA in Arabic 0945 GMT 11 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC1103104194 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] London, 11 Mar (MENA)--Egyptian Interior Minister 
Major General Hasan al-Alfi has stated that the security 
services recently foiled several terror schemes. 
  He told the London-based Arabic daily AL-HAYAH that police 
identified and monitored the extremist groups after tightening 
control of desert areas, shanty towns, and Nile islands, where 
those groups had their secret hideouts. 
  Al-Alfi stressed that foreign quarters are involved in the 
terrorist operations in Egypt. 
  He said police are constantly directing abortive blows at 
terrorist schemes. The arrest of those involved in recent bank 
bombings in Cairo and al-Jizah comes within this context, he 
said. 
  The interior minister renewed rejection of a dialogue with 
the terrorists. 
  He said terrorists try to create what he described as "media 
furor." Some foreign news media help them by inflating their 
operations, he noted. 
  Al-Alfi said Egyptian security agencies are watching 
developments in the structure of the terrorist groups on every 
level, beginning with relations among them and ending with the 
splits and alliances that affect changes of membership. 
  He said Egypt is in constant touch with foreign states where 
some extremist leaders reside. 
  Al-Alfi said the lack of indictment against Ayman 
al-Zawahiri, an al-Jihad organization leader now living in 
Switzerland, in the case of the attempt on Prime Minister 'Atif 
Sidqi's life concerns the interrogation authorities. Perhaps 
those authorities don't have enough evidence for an indictment, 
he said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

