<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Peres Views al-Asad-Darawshah Meeting, Remarks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA1003062194 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Hebrew 0505 GMT 10 
Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA1003062194 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hebrew </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Telephone interview with Foreign Minister Shim'on Peres by </F>
Hayim Zissowitz -- live] 
  [Excerpt] [passage omitted] [Zissowitz] Let us talk about 
the Syrian track of the peace talks, which has not been affected 
-- or has been less affected -- by the Hebron massacre. Did you 
read the minutes of the meeting between Knesset Member [MK] 
'Abd-al-Wahhab Darawshah and Syrian President Hafiz al-Asad 
yesterday? 
  [Peres] Yes. 
  [Zissowitz] Did you detect any new messages? 
  [Peres] No, I just detected softer language. It is 
interesting to note that this was a meeting between the Syrian 
president and Israeli representatives, although they did not 
enter the country with their Israeli passports and did not 
highlight the fact that they are Israelis and members of the 
Knesset. This, too, is one of the signs of the times. 
  You know, we have long outgrown the era of charades, of 
hiding, disguising, and pretending. What good is it? That, 
however, seems to be the way of the world up north. 
  [Zissowitz] In the meeting, President al-Asad reiterated his 
formula of full peace in exchange for full withdrawal. Is 
Israel prepared to accept such a formula? 
  [Peres] First of all, I do not know what full peace is. 
When he talks about full peace, what is it filled with? For 
example, he did not undertake to fill it with diplomatic 
representations, commercial ties, and open borders. So what 
does full mean? 
  [Zissowitz] Did you hear the utterances of MK's Talib 
al-Sani' and Darawshah during a tour of the Golan Heights and in 
other meetings? 
  [Peres] I think they are both MK's, and whatever their 
criticism of Israel is, they should voice it in Jerusalem rather 
than in al-Qunaytirah. In my opinion, both good manners and 
logic call for highlighting the positive and the things we have 
in common. 
  [Zissowitz] Do Israeli MK's who talk on the Syrian side of 
the Golan Heights about the terrible oppression of the 
Palestinians and who say that the lot of Israel's Arabs is worse 
than that of Syria's Jews truly represent Israeli Arabs? 
  [Peres] I do not believe that. I do not recall the Syrian 
Parliament ever having had a Jewish member. As you know, every 
Syrian Jew may come to Israel, but can every Israeli Arab go to 
Syria? We all know that not even all Arabs are allowed in, but 
only people who belong to a certain party, group, and belief. 
Even then, they are not issued passports or allowed to 
publicize their identity. In this respect, if you were to 
compare the Israeli delegation's visit to Syria with visits to 
Israel by foreign delegations to meet with Arabs and others, the 
difference would immediately strike you. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-13258 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes048_l_94008" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-048 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  11 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kahana Hay Leader Jailed After Conviction </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA1003150694 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Hebrew 1400 GMT 10 
Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA1003150694 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hebrew </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Hadera Magistrate's Court sentenced Binyamin 
Kahana, the leader of the Kahana Hay movement, to nine months in 
prison after convicting him of assaulting a policeman and 
violating an injunction that was issued against him. 
  Our correspondent Nati Zilberman reports that the incident 
took place approximately two years ago during a demonstration in 
Umm al-Fahm. Binyamin Kahana was placed under arrest and jailed 
immediately after today's hearing. 

</TEXT>

