<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry Scores UN Human Rights Resolution </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC1103105794 Tehran Voice of the Islamic Republic of Iran 
First Program Network in Persian 0430 GMT 11 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC1103105794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tehran Voice of the Islamic Republic of Iran 
First Program Network </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Persian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Following the approval of a resolution against the 
Islamic Republic of Iran by the UN Human Rights Commission 
[UNHRC], our Foreign Ministry issued a statement today in which 
it strongly condemns the irresponsible act by the UNHRC and says 
that this resolution stems from the political intentions of the 
regime occupying Jerusalem. 
  Our Foreign Ministry's statement clarifies that the United 
States and the other mentors of Zionism who were the ringleaders 
in pushing the issuance of such a resolution have all remained 
silent on the massacre of fasting Muslims in the al-Ibrahimi 
Mosque in Hebron and have even prevented the issuance of a 
resolution condemning the Zionist regime by the UN Security 
Council. Therefore, under the current conditions the Islamic 
Republic of Iran considers this resolution to be a manifestation 
of the spite of the Western-Zionist circles vis-a-vis the 
Islamic Republic of Iran's independent policies, its defiance of 
superpower domination, and especially its refusal to assist in 
imposing humiliation on the Palestinian nation. 
  It has now been proven to the world that the Western 
countries who support such resolutions have been hypocritically 
assisting in the inhuman crimes and flagrant violations of human 
rights in Bosnia-Herzegovina in the heart of Europe for a long 
time. 
  The statement also refers to the political and social rights 
of the minorities in the Islamic Republic of Iran and to the 
fact that penal codes in Iran are based on the judicial system 
of Islam accepted and respected by more than 1 billion Muslims 
throughout the world, and emphasizes that the issuance of such 
resolutions mars the credibility of such forums. 

</TEXT>

