<F P=100> JORDAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Weekly on Purposes of King's Saudi Pilgrimage </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  JN1003134794 Amman AKHBAR AL-USBU' in Arabic 10 Mar 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> JN1003134794 </F>
<F P=104>  Amman AKHBAR AL-USBU' </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] During his visit to the tomb of his great 
grandfather Prophet Muhammad, God's peace and blessings be upon 
him, in Medina, and during his circumambulation in Mecca, His 
Majesty King Husayn reminded the Islamic nation on the night of 
al-Qadr [the night the koran was revealed] of the importance of 
Islamic and Arab solidarity against the ferocious onslaught 
against Muslims and Arabs. King Husayn's gesture is not new; it 
stems from the continuous role the Hashemites have played in 
unifying the Arabs and Muslims throughout the ages. It also 
indicates that this blessed month is the month of communication, 
amity, and love among the Muslims in all their countries. In 
addition to performing the minor pilgrimage, the king's visit to 
Mecca and Medina sought to intensify Islamic and Arab efforts, 
which stem from the Hashemites' struggle in national, pan-Arab, 
and humanitarian Jordan, to unite in rank, word, and position. 
Jordan rose above the pan-Arab wounds to heal the rift which 
afflicted the Arab homeland after the Gulf war for the sake of 
restoring Arab solidarity and reactivating joint Arab action 
that can confront the serious challenges threatening the Arab 
and Islamic nation. 

</TEXT>

