<F P=100> SOUTH ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Afghanistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rabbani Agrees to 15-day Cease-Fire </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1303195994 Tehran IRIB Television Third Program Network in 
Persian 1915 GMT 13 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1303195994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tehran IRIB Television Third Program Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Persian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Afghan President Rabbani agreed today to a 15-day 
cease-fire, but it was not clear whether his main rivals would 
support the truce or carry on rocketing the battered capital. 
  Despite Rabbani's plea, most people expect more fighting. 
Countless cease-fire agreements have collapsed and the current 
fighting is perhaps the most intense since the ousting of the 
communist government in 1992. 
  The latest cease-fire plan has been negotiated by military 
and political leaders from southwestern Afghanistan who recently 
arrived in Kabul. Since the fighting started 1 January, at 
least 1,000 people have been killed, more than 12,000 have been 
wounded, and some 600,000 have been driven from their homes. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

