<F P=100> India </F>
<H3> <TI>   Minister Rules Out Visit of Islamic Mission to Kashmir </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK1103090794 Delhi All India Radio Network in English 0830 
GMT 11 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK1103090794 </F>
<F P=104>  Delhi All India Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] New Delhi has expressed the hope that Pakistan will 
now return to bilateral talks with India on the Kashmir issue 
following its setback in Geneva. The minister of state for 
external affairs, Mr. Salman Khurshid, told a press conference 
in New Delhi today that India had a clear margin to defeat 
Pakistan's resolution on Kashmir if it had been put to vote. 
Mr. Khurshid, who returned from Geneva last night, said that 
there was overwhelming opinion that the bilateral issue should 
not be raised at Human Rights Commission forum. He denied 
entering into any tripartite deal with Iran and China to enable 
withdrawal of the Pakistan-sponsored resolution. Mr. Khurshid 
also ruled out any fact-finding commission of the Islamic 
conference Organization to Kashmir. He, however, disclosed that 
India has invited the permanent representatives of the ICO at 
Geneva to visit New Delhi for discussions. 

</TEXT>

