<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Kuwait </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ambassador To Return to Qatar After Ramadan </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC1203220494 Paris AFP in English 2150 GMT 12 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC1203220494 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Kuwait City, March 12 (AFP) -- The Kuwaiti 
ambassador to Qatar is to return to his post after having been 
recalled recently amid strengthening ties between Qatar and 
Iraq, a Sunday paper reported here. 
  The daily AL-QABAS said in its Sunday edition that Muhammad 
al-Rumi would return to Doha after celebrations for the end of 
Ramadan, the Moslem month of fasting. 
  The paper said, quoting the Kuwaiti foreign ministry, that 
al-Rumi had been recalled for talks after television reports in 
Doha on the situation in Iraq and the impact of a UN-imposed 
embargo. 
  Kuwait recalled al-Rumi in mid-February and protested to the 
Qatar government for allowing the official television to give 
airtime to Iraqi leaders. 
  Apart from Oman, which never broke off links with Iraq, 
Qatar 
is the only member of the Gulf Cooperation Council, to have 
renewed ties with Baghdad since its invasion of Kuwait in August 
1990 which sparked the Gulf war. 

</TEXT>

