<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   President Calls for Talks To Resolve Crisis </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC1203191694 Paris AFP in English 1753 GMT 12 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC1203191694 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Sanaa, March 12 (AFP) -- President 'Ali 'Abdallah 
Salih Saturday urged the people of Yemen to oppose any attempt 
to divide the country, calling for talks to resolve its 
seven-month-old political crisis. 
  In a national address marking the end of the Moslem fasting 
month of Ramadan, he said: "We must not tolerate any attempts to 
break the country's unity or to provoke sedition or war." 
  North and South Yemen were unified in May 1990, but a crisis 
broke out in August when Vice President 'Ali Salim al-Bid, a 
southerner, refused to take up his duties in Sanaa, demanding 
major political and economic reforms. 
  Salih, a northerner, added: "Those who think Yemen's 
problems 
can be solved by dividing (the country) are wrong." 
  He called for talks to resolve all differences with al-Bid, 
his main political rival. 
  Tensions have been building in Yemen in recent weeks between 
rival north and south armies, despite a February 20 
reconciliation accord. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

