<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   Vice Chairman Comments on `Anti-Arab' Scheme </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC1303085194 Cairo MENA in Arabic 0730 GMT 13 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC1303085194 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 13 Mar (MENA)--'Ali Salim al-Bid, vice 
chairman of the Yemeni Presidential Council and leader of the 
Yemeni Socialist Party, has warned that an anti-Arab scheme is 
being planned to spread terrorism and extremism with a view to 
harming the ambitions of the Arab and Islamic nation and 
isolating it from the rest of the world. 
  In a statement to AL-AHRAM published today, al-Bid says that 
the features of this terrorist scheme are clear to all, and its 
threat extends to a number of Arab countries. 
  He called for confronting the scheme by bringing it up for 
discussion at the pan-Arab level. He said the backward 
mentalities that want to impose their control on the Arab and 
Islamic nation must be confronted. 
  Al-Bid welcomed any Arab effort to steer unified Yemen clear 
of the specter of civil war and help the country to continue its 
democratic and peaceful march and adhere to the Pledge and 
Accord Document on national reconciliation. 
  He praised the efforts of Egypt and President Husni Mubarak 
to contain the Yemeni crisis. He said Egypt, by virtue of its 
relations with and assistance to Yemen, can play an effective 
role on the Yemeni scene. 
  On the situation in Yemen, al-Bid said: From experience, we 
have come to realize that Yemen had neither the right 
circumstances nor the suitable leadership for unity of action in 
the past. 
  Some believed the signing of the Pledge and Accord Document 
ended the crisis, but this is wrong; the signing meant only that 
we acknowledged the crisis and laid down the bases to resolve 
it, he said. 
  "The situation requires that we move toward implementation 
in 
the appropriate circumstances," he added. 
  On fears that a military confrontation may break out in 
Yemen, al-Bid said there are such fears, and the Military 
Committee needs help from Arab forces -- especially Egypt, which 
is the closest Arab country to us -- so that a civil war can be 
avoided. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

