<F P=100> ARAB AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Algeria </F>
<H3> <TI>   Muslim Fundamentalists Escape in Mass Jail Break </TI></H3>
<H4>   Manhunt Launched </H4>
<F P=102> NC1203103894 Paris AFP in English 1006 GMT 12 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC1203103894 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Algiers, March 12 (AFP) -- Security forces were 
engaged in a massive manhunt Saturday for about 1,000 prisoners, 
including 100 Moslem fundamentalists on death row, who escaped 
when Islamic guerrillas stormed their prison, reliable sources 
said. 
  Police, gendarmes and troops launched a joint security sweep 
using helicopters to search the mountainous area near Tazoult, 
400 kilometres (240 miles) southeast of the capital, following 
Thursday's mass breakout. 
  Their search is being hampered by the difficult terrain 
which 
nationalist fighters used to hole up during the 1954-62 war of 
independence from France. 
  The Algerian authorities has so far refused to officially 
confirm the escape, the most spectacular since the start of 
fundamentalist violence in Algeria two years ago. 
  The Algerian authorities have rounded up thousands in a 
crackdown on Islamic fundamentalists who launched a bloody 
guerrilla war against the secular administration following the 
January 1992 cancellation of a general election the now outlawed 
Islamic Salvation Front (FIS) was poised to win. 
  According to the sources around 150 Islamic guerrillas 
attacked the prison around 7:00 p.m. (1800 GMT) on Thursday 
during the Ramadan meal break when security was lax, killing 
four prison warders, the sources added. 
  It was not clear whether the operation had been launched by 
the Islamic Group (GIA) or its rival Armed Islamic Movement 
(MIA), the sources said. 
  Some 400 fundamentalists serving life sentences also escaped 
in the jail break, as well as 200 criminals with common law 
convictions. 
  Tazoult prison accommodates 3,000 detainees, many of them 
considered particularly dangerous. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

