<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Action Shows Return to `Bias Toward Israel' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM1103150994 London AL-HAYAH in Arabic 11 Mar 94 pp 1, 4 </F>
<F P=103> PM1103150994 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-HAYAH </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Rafiq al-Ma'luf, Raghidah Dirgham, 'Ali Nun, and </F>
Jalal al-Mashtah: "Washington Tells PLO To Negotiate 
Unconditionally"] 
  [Excerpts] Washington, New York, London, Moscow -- Over the 
past 48 hours the United States has escalated its position, 
preventing the Security Council voting on a resolution on the 
Hebron massacre, on the pretext of a disagreement over one word 
in the draft resolution. Also, Secretary of State Warren 
Christopher requested President Yasir 'Arafat to resume the 
negotiations with Israel "without prior conditions." While 
Moscow announced that Foreign Minister Andrey Kozyrev will visit 
the region today. 
  Responding to this, a high-ranking Palestinian source 
contacted by AL-HAYAH accused Ambassador Dennis Ross, U.S. 
coordinator of the peace process, and the official in charge of 
the Middle East at the National Security Council "of returning 
to complete bias toward Israel and exploiting President 
Clinton's preoccupation with domestic matters to take control of 
U.S. foreign policy." [passage omitted] 
  A PLO official, who asked to remain anonymous, pointed out 
that Christopher had phoned President 'Arafat and demanded that 
the PLO resume the negotiations without any prior conditions or 
agree to hold meetings between Palestinian and Israeli officials. 
  The official said: "It is clear that the U.S. Administration 
is exerting pressure (on the PLO) in Israel's favor through its 
threat to use the veto." [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-13352 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes049_h_94001" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-049 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  14 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Tunisia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ben Ali, 'Arafat Discuss Message From U.S. Envoy </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1103203194 Tunis Tunis-7 Television in Arabic 1900 GMT 11 
Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1103203194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tunis Tunis-7 Television </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Regarding presidential activities, President 
Zine El Abidine Ben Ali at noon today at the Carthage Palace met 
with the Palestinian president Yasir 'Arafat. [passage omitted]. 
  President Yasir 'Arafat said that his meeting with His 
Excellency the President dealt with the deliberations of the UN 
Security Council regarding the massacre of the al-Ibrahimi 
mosque. In this connection he said that the fact that the 
Council has not adopted a resolution seriously affects the 
situation inside the occupied territories as a whole. He added 
that he had informed President Zine El Abidine Ben Ali of the 
aspects of the message he received last night from the U.S. 
Secretary of State Mr. Warren Christopher which dealt with the 
importance of the continuation and movement forward of the 
peace process. President 'Arafat renewed in this regard the 
Palestinian stance which stresses the necessity of issuing a 
strong resolution by the Security Council which takes into 
account the issue of Jerusalem and the condemnation of the 
attack on the al-Ibrahimi mosque and the adoption of immediate 
international measures to protect the Palestinian people. Mr. 
Arafat said that he had thanked President Zine El Abidine Ben 
Ali for the efforts he had made one more than one level to 
overcome these difficulties, hoping to arrive at a resolution 
that protect the Palestinian people from all attacks. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

