<F P=100> Egypt </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Big Powers' Asked To Stop Leveling Accusations at Arabs </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC1203215494 Cairo MENA in Arabic 2058 GMT 12 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC1203215494 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 12 Mar (MENA)--The newspaper AL-AHRAM has 
asked the big powers to stop leveling accusations at the Arab 
countries, especially under the current circumstances, or to 
control them, particularly since there are some sides who are 
committing crimes in broad daylight and no one is taking any 
measures against them. 
  The paper said in its comment for tomorrow, Sunday, that 
most 
of these accusations come from one big power with interests in 
the region. It has some relationship to the issue at which 
accusations are being leveled. The paper added that these 
accusations are not based on anything other than reports 
containing unconfirmed information or guesswork. 
  It added that these accusations are linked to some kind of 
violation of international peace and security, which means that 
the road is now open for taking the necessary resolutions 
accompanied by certain sanctions on the part of the Security 
Council. 
  The paper said that Iraq was previously accused of using gas 
against the Shiites in the marshlands. After investigations, it 
was proven that this had not taken place. Libya was also 
accused of setting up installations for producing chemical 
weapons -- an accusation for which there is no evidence to back 
it up. Similar accusations have been leveled at other Arab 
countries. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

