<H3> <TI>   U.S. Coordinator's Visit to Tunis Said Postponed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC1203185494 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1730 GMT 12 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC1203185494 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tunis, 12 Mar (MENA)--Informed Palestinian sources 
have stated that Washington has postponed for a few days the 
visit to Tunis by Dennis Ross, U.S. coordinator of the Middle 
East peace process, to meet with Palestinian President Yasir 
'Arafat. The visit was scheduled for today to discuss the 
results of Russian Foreign Minister Andrey Kozyrev's visit to 
Tunis and his meeting with PLO Chairman Yasir 'Arafat last night. 
  The visit has been postponed despite the PLO's approval for 
receiving Ross today in accordance with a proposal by U.S. 
Secretary of State Warren Christopher in his message to 'Arafat 
yesterday. Under the proposal, Ross was scheduled to visit Tunis 
and Israel today and tomorrow as part of the ongoing efforts to 
bring the PLO back to the peace talks. 
  The same sources pointed out that perhaps Washington is 
worried about Kozyrev's visit to Tunis and his meeting with 
'Arafat, which were made as part of a unilateral Russian 
initiative without coordination with the United States. 

</TEXT>

