<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Negotiations Break Off Seriously Considered </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC1103133794 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1245 GMT 11 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC1103133794 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tunis, 11 Mar (MENA)--Press reports published here 
today said that the Palestinian leadership is seriously thinking 
of officially announcing the break-off of negotiations with 
Israel. 
  These reports included a statement by an informed 
Palestinian 
source in Tunis which says that this development in the 
Palestinian stand comes in the wake of the failure of all 
political and diplomatic efforts and moves led by the PLO since 
the al-Ibrahimi Mosque massacre at all levels to make Israel 
respond to the Palestinian demands to disarm the settlers in the 
occupied territories and to provide an international presence to 
protect the Palestinians living under the occupation. 
  The Palestinian source added that the Palestinian leadership 
is following with concern the premeditated U.S. prevarication 
aiming to thwart a Security Council resolution on the 
al-Ibrahimi Mosque massacre, especially in light of the 
insinuations by a number of officials in the U.S. Mission at the 
United Nations on the possibility of delaying the Security 
Council debate on the issue until further notice. 
  This source revealed that the Palestinian leadership has 
received demands from Palestine National Council members and a 
number of national figures in the occupied territories demanding 
the breaking off of negotiations. 
  The Tunisian newspaper AL-SABAH today cited a prominent 
Palestinian source as saying that the Palestinian leadership is 
still continuing diplomatic efforts in an attempt to break the 
deadlock in the negotiations. This source did not rule out the 
possibility that the coming few days could be decisive for 
either speeding up the peace process or closing this file for 
good. 
  The same paper also cites informed Palestinian sources as 
saying that Palestinian President Yasir 'Arafat refrained from 
following up on the telephone call he received from Israeli 
Prime Minister Yitzhaq Rabin the day before yesterday lest any 
talk could be construed as a return to the peace negotiations, 
which were halted as a result of the al-Ibrahimi Mosque massacre. 
  The sources added that 'Arafat explained this position as 
insistence on the official and popular Palestinian stand of 
waiting for a clear resolution from the Security Council that 
condemns the massacre and its perpetrators, sends international 
observers to the occupied territories, demands the disarming of 
the settlers and the removal of the settlements, and ensures 
security. 
  They added that the PLO command also wants to know the 
results of the official Israeli investigation and the identity 
of those responsible for not providing protection for the 
worshipers in the al-Ibrahimi Mosque. 
  Regarding the several contacts held recently between the 
Palestinian leadership and Russian envoys, the Palestinian 
source said that Russia now has new and positive stands on the 
issue of peace in the Middle East and these stands stem from the 
restoration of the Russian political leadership's 
self-confidence resulting from defusing the armed conflict 
between Serbia and NATO over Bosnia. The source noted that 
Russian Foreign Minister Andrey Kozyrev will visit Tunis in the 
next 48 hours to continue the consultations and efforts on the 
Middle East. It said that Russia supports the Palestinian 
demands and the Palestinian side agrees to the Russian proposal 
to hold a second international conference on the Middle East, 
which will be a new Madrid conference. The source expressed the 
belief that Russia has made a strong and influential return to 
the Middle East on the basis of a new concept of its relations 
with the countries of the region. 
  It said that the PLO will hold meetings at the Executive 
Committee, expanded leadership, and possibly the Central Council 
levels in the next few days to assess the situation. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-13394 </DOCNO>
