<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kakh To `Suspend' Activity Pending Ruling </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA1303175394 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Hebrew 1600 GMT 13 
Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA1303175394 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hebrew </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Kakh movement has announced that it will submit 
an appeal to the High Court of Justice against the decision to 
declare it a terrorist organization. The organization said that 
it would temporarily suspend its activity pending the High 
Court's ruling. 
  Our correspondent Gil Litman reports that in its 
announcement, the Kakh movement asserted that all its activity 
had been carried out within the framework of the law. 
  Justice Minister David Liba'i said that the Justice Ministry 
was currently preparing an amendment to the Antiterror Act 
according to which the judiciary, and not the Israeli 
Government, would be made responsible for declaring which groups 
constituted terrorist organizations. 
  Here are some reactions to the cabinet's decision to declare 
the Kakh and Kahana Hay movements terrorist organizations: PLO 
official Abu-al-'Ala' said that although this constituted a 
positive step, it was too little in relation to the enormity of 
the Hebron massacre. Likud Knesset Member [MK] Mikha'el Eytan 
said that the decision came too late. Such a decision, he said, 
should already have been made by earlier Likud governments. 
Mikha'el Eytan added that many people had been led astray by 
these movements. 
  The Committee of Arab Local Councils welcomed the decision 
but said that it was not enough. The settlers should be taken 
out of Hebron and those capable of harming the fabric of 
relations between Jews and Arabs should be disarmed. 
  Uri Ari'el, the secretary general of the Council of Jewish 
Settlements in Judaea, Samaria, and the Gaza Strip, said that 
the decision should have been made by a court and not by the 
executive level. 

</TEXT>

