<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rabin Reportedly Not To Evacuate Hebron Settlers </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA1303095994 Tel Aviv YEDI'OT AHARONOT in Hebrew 13 Mar 94 
pp 1, 15 </F>

<F P=103> TA1303095994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tel Aviv YEDI'OT AHARONOT </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hebrew </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by political correspondent Shim'on Schiffer] </F>
  [Text] Prime Minister Yitzhaq Rabin does not intend to do 
anything about evacuating the Jewish settlers from Hebron and 
transferring them to Qiryat Arba' or other locations. 
  Rabin believes that such a move would set a dangerous 
precedent that would serve as an incentive for the Palestinian 
terrorist organizations operating against the settlements in the 
territories. 
  Rabin transmitted his position on the matter to U.S. 
Administration sources with whom he spoke over recent days. In 
the prime minister's view, a decision to evacuate the Hebron 
settlers would also lead to the opening of the Israeli-PLO 
agreement, which is contrary to Israel's current interest. 
  A majority was developing in the cabinet last week for 
evacuating the settlers in Hebron, mainly for security reasons. 
  The United States is exerting pressure on Rabin to take a 
series of steps to make it easier for 'Arafat to return to the 
negotiating table following the Hebron massacre. The U.S. 
Administration is pressuring for a withdrawal of the IDF [Israel 
Defense Forces] from Hebron's central bus station. The 
Americans claim that if Rabin cannot evacuate the settlers, then 
he can at least make a gesture to the Arabs in Hebron, and 
evacuate the central bus station area, which the IDF took 
control of several months ago. 
  Rabin has so far also rejected this U.S. request, claiming 
that planned Palestinian retaliation against the Hebron settlers 
is prohibiting any thinning of forces or a withdrawal from the 
bus station. Rabin made it clear to the Americans that he 
cannot and will not do anything beyond what he has already done 
to tighten supervision over the settlers. 
  In talks the prime minister will hold in Washington this 
week, he will also raise the issue of growing military 
cooperation being between Russia and Syria, in the wake of 
recent reports reaching Israel that Russia has renewed contacts 
with Syria, offering it sophisticated military equipment. 
  Rabin is due to inform the cabinet today of steps he intends 
to take to outlaw Kakh and Kahana Hay, based on Attorney General 
Mikha'el Ben-Ya'ir's opinion, presented to the prime minister 
over the weekend. The opinion advocates measures to declare 
them terrorist organizations under the antiterrorism law. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-13416 </DOCNO>
