<H3> <TI>   Russian Foreign Minister Holds Talks With Rabin </TI></H3>
<H4>   Rabin Accepts Invitation to Moscow </H4>
<F P=102> TA1403100094 Tel Aviv YEDI'OT AHARONOT in Hebrew 14 Mar 94 
pp 1, 19 </F>

<F P=103> TA1403100094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tel Aviv YEDI'OT AHARONOT </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hebrew </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by political correspondent Shim'on Schiffer] </F>
  [Excerpt] [passage omitted] Prime Minister Yitzhaq Rabin 
is due to depart for Washington this evening. At the beginning 
of April he will travel to Moscow for political talks with 
Russian President Boris Yeltsin. 
  Yeltsin sent Rabin a message yesterday with a special 
courier 
in which he invites Rabin for a meeting to discuss the political 
process, as well as issues pertaining to Israeli-Russian 
relations. Rabin accepted the invitation. 
  In recent days, the prime minister has voiced his concern 
about Russia's wish to resume an active role in the region. 
Rabin publicly voiced his displeasure after meeting with the 
Russian foreign minister and his deputy, who recently came to 
Israel in a bid to mediate between it and the PLO. 
  It seems that the Russians were hurt by the way their envoys 
were received in Israel and consequently proceeded to arrange a 
meeting between Rabin and Yeltsin. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

