<F P=100> Iran </F>
<H3> <TI>   Oil Expert Blames Saudi Overproduction for Low Prices </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1403101294 Tehran IRNA in English 0943 GMT 14 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1403101294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tehran IRNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tehran, March 14, IRNA -- Saudi Arabia's 
over-production, besides other factors such as the international 
economic recession, is responsible for the continued low oil 
price, said an oil expert here last week. A former high-ranking 
Oil Ministry official who requested anonimity told the bilingual 
weekly 'KAYHAN HAVA'I' that Saudi Arabia was producing about 9.5 
million barrels per day, 1.5 million more than its official OPEC 
quota. 
  "If Saudi Arabia abides by the OPEC agreement and reduces 
its 
oil output, oil prices will jump up", he told the weekly. 
  Brent North Sea crude oil last week crashed to a low of 
dlrs. 
13.5 a barrel, its lowest level for six years. Oil prices 
further plummeted last week after OPEC members of the (Persian) 
Gulf Cooperation Council ended a meeting without reaching 
agreement to reduce their oil output. "There is no evidence to 
prove that Saudi Arabia will agree to a lower quota in the 
upcoming OPEC meeting", the former Oil Ministry official said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

