<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-050 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  12 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> JORDAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Paper Attacks `Arbitrary' U.S. Policies at UN </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  JN1203112594 Amman SAWT AL-SHA'B in Arabic 12 Mar 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> JN1203112594 </F>
<F P=104>  Amman SAWT AL-SHA'B </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Editorial: "U.S. Arbitrariness at the Security Council"] </F>
  [Text] The United States is continuing its arbitrary 
policies and showing its disdain for the Arab nation through the 
farce of consultations that the UN Security Council has been 
carrying out for the last two weeks over the massacre of the age 
committed by the Zionist gangs in the holy al-Ibrahimi Mosque in 
Hebron. 
  When we say the Security Council, we in fact mean the U.S. 
Administration that has imposed its full control and hegemony 
over the international organization since the Gulf crisis in 
1990 and the subsequent host of unjust resolutions adopted, in 
record time, against fraternal Iraq. The Iraqi people are still 
suffering from the effects of these unjust and unprecedented 
resolutions even though their alleged justifications are over. 
  Within less than two weeks, the Security Council adopted 
some 
13 resolutions, including a resolution that allowed the 
launching of a brutal aggression against Iraq, in addition to 
the imposition of an all-out siege. On the other hand, the 
council has spent two full weeks on consultations on the most 
brutal and unprecedented massacre in contemporary history. 
These consultations have been subject to strange U.S. 
bargaining. This bargaining has once again shown the hypocrisy, 
double-standards, and blatant contradictions in U.S. political 
behavior. It has exposed the allegations about eagerness to 
implement international legitimacy and UN resolutions. 
  The final straw in this U.S. bargaining was the humiliating 
condition set by Christopher in his telephone contact with 
Palestinian President Yasir 'Arafat last Thursday. Christopher 
emphasized his administration's position, which forms a link 
between any proposed international resolution condemning the 
massacre and the resumption of the Palestinian-Israeli 
negotiations, despite the fact that the U.S. position on the 
draft resolution is not far from what Israeli wants. Washington 
insists on a diluted resolution that does not contain any 
serious measures to deter the Israelis from their repressive 
policy in the occupied Arab territories. 
  We have never had a good opinion of U.S. intentions toward 
our just Arab causes. We have never ignored the nature of the 
strategic alliance between the United States and Israel, which 
has continued for decades, or the unlimited U.S. support for 
Zionist aggressiveness against the Arab nation. We are fully 
aware that restoring respect and dignity to this nation cannot 
be realized through the emotions of the United States, because 
politics and interests do not know emotions. There is no 
alternative for Arab solidarity, even the minimum of this 
solidarity. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

