<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Al-Husayni Views Resuming Peace Negotiations </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  JN1403195394 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Arabic 1530 GMT 14 
Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN1403195394 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with Faysal al-Husayni, Fatah leader in the </F>
occupied territories and Palestinian negotiator, by Sa'id 
Mu'addi; place and date not given; from the "With the Events" 
program--recorded] 
  [Text] [Mu'addi] Mr. Faysal al-Husayni: The Kakh and 
Kahana Hay movements have been outlawed. How does the 
Palestinian side view the [Israeli] Government's decision in 
this regard? 
  [Al-Husayni] First, I believe this decision came too late. 
It was unnecessary to commit the [Hebron] massacre in order to 
make such a decision. In any case, to make such a decision--no 
matter how late--is better than not to make any decision. 
However, what is more important than making this decision is 
implementing it, and figuring out how to do it. Will this 
actually be a battle against all these settlers who are opposed 
to the peace process and the idea of peace, or will its 
implementation be confined to those whose membership in Kakh is 
confirmed? 
  [Mu'addi] What can be done immediately to ease the tension 
prevailing in the Palestinian streets in the wake of this 
incident? 
  [Al-Husayni] First, I believe that the settlers residing in 
Hebron should be evacuated. In addition, arrangements should be 
made to protect the Palestinian people's security. Such 
arrangements should include the issue of arming the settlers 
everywhere. We believe that these settlers should be disarmed, 
and that the army, and not the settlers, should maintain 
security, especially since many of these settlers engaged in 
settlement activities from the very beginning in order to 
achieve a single objective; namely, to foil this political 
process. 
  We also believe that the file of settlements should be 
opened 
at the negotiating table because this directly concerns the 
Palestinian people's security. This issue should thus be 
discussed. Discussions should not be confined to the Israeli 
people's security, as was the case in the past. 
  [Mu'addi] Do you believe that Israeli-Palestinian 
negotiations may resume next week in light of the intensive 
consultations and contacts in Tunis, Washington, and Jerusalem? 
  [Al-Husayni] In fact, it depends on the practices on the 
ground in terms of evacuating the settlers and releasing the 
Palestinian detainees. All these issues, together, can pave the 
way for the resumption of negotiations. I believe it is almost 
impossible to resume negotiations without making any kind of 
implementation on the ground. 
  [Mu'addi] Mr. Faysal al-Husayni: Thank you very much, and 
many happy returns ['Id greetings]. 
  [Al-Husayni] Same to you. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-13490 </DOCNO>
