<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Reaction to Kakh Ban Seen as `Lukewarm' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA1503061394 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in English 0500 GMT 15 
Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA1503061394 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Israeli sources in Washington have expressed 
disappointment with what they say was a lukewarm response by the 
State Department spokeswoman, Christine Shelly, on the Israel 
Government's decision to outlaw Kakh and Kahana Hay. She was 
quoted as saying the decision should be seen as part of the 
overall effort Israel is making to meet Palestinian security 
concerns. She also said the United States is considering 
whether to put Kakh and Kahana Hay on its list of terrorist 
sponsors. Christine Shelly told reporters yesterday that Kakh 
and Kahana Hay, on the basis of their words and actions, have 
advocated and engaged in terrorism. Shelly added that U.S. law 
had provisions for curtailing fund-raising for such groups in 
the United States. 
  [Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Hebrew at 0500 GMT on 15 March, 
in 
a similar report, adds that "Israel's Ambassador in Washington 
Itamar Rabinovich told our correspondent Arye Golan that senior 
State Department officials had reacted very positively to the 
steps taken by the Israeli Government in the wake of the Hebron 
massacre."] 

</TEXT>

