<F P=100> Iran </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tehran's Intervention on Kashmir Issue Criticized </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC1503054594 Paris AFP in English 1233 GMT 14 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC1503054594 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tehran, March 14 (AFP) -- A radical Iranian daily on 
Monday criticised the government for pressuring Pakistan into 
withdrawing a UN resolution condemning India's human rights 
record in Kashmir. 
  "Given India's black record in Kashmir, is it possible to 
absolve New Delhi of the savage killing of men, women and 
children?" asked Jomhuri-e Eslami, close to Islamic hardliners. 
Had the intervention been in the "long-term interest of a 
Moslem nation and the liberation movements in Kashmir?" 
  The daily urged the foreign ministry to explain the logic 
behind the intervention to the Kashmiri people in order to 
"reassure them that Iran has made no changes in its position." 
  Islamabad dropped the resolution to be put before the UN 
Human Rights Commission in Geneva at the last minute Wednesday 
after pressure from Iran, China and other countries. 
  The initial draft resolution proposed that the commission 
express "its grave concern at the gross and consistent 
violations of human rights in Jammu and Kashmir." 
  On Thursday, a Moslem rebel group in Kashmir charged the 
Iranian stand on the disputed state had been an about-turn. 
  More than 8,500 people have died in Kashmir since 1989 when 
Moslem militants stepped up a bloody campaign for succession. 

</TEXT>

