<F P=100> Iran </F>
<H3> <TI>   Majles, Guardian Council Amend Budget </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1503104294 Tehran IRNA in English 1008 GMT 15 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1503104294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tehran IRNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tehran, March 15, IRNA -- Iran's Islamic 
Consultative Assembly (Majlis) here Monday discussed points in 
the next year budget bill referred to by the Council of 
Guardians as incorrect and made amendments in order to receive 
the Council's final approval. 
  The Council of Guardians had found faults with the bill 
concerning articles 52th and 53 of the Constitution. It had 
also referred to some of the notes in the bill as ambiguous and 
against Islamic law. According to the 53th article of the 
Constitution the whole money the government gains is 
concentrated in the state treasury and all payments are 
performed on the basis of the approved credits and according to 
the law. 
  Article 52 says that the country's annual budget should be 
proposed by the government as stipulated by the law and should 
be submitted to the Majlis for deliberations and approval. Any 
change in the figures should be according to the law as well. 
  After the Majlis completed debates over the next year budget 
bill in its open session Wednesday, the bill was sent to the 
Council of Guardians for final approval. The Council, after 
some study, returned the bill to the Majlis to correct the 
faults. 
  The Majlis did some amendments to the bill in its Saturday 
session but the council regarded the amendments as insufficient 
and retured the bill to the Majlis for the second time. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

