<H3> <TI>   Minister Urges Pakistan To Keep `Open Mind' on Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK1203123294 Delhi All India Radio Network in English 0245 
GMT 12 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK1203123294 </F>
<F P=104>  Delhi All India Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] New Delhi says that Kashmir issue can be resolved if 
Islamabad has an open mind on bilateral dialogue. In an 
interview to AIR correspondent Sebastian Roberts in the 
Spotlight Program last night, the minister of state for external 
affairs, Mr. Salman Khurshid, said bilateral discussion is the 
only way to solve the problem, but Islamabad cannot expect that 
India should concede all its demands. He made it clear that New 
Delhi will do everything possible for the resumption of 
bilateral discussions. 
  Replying to a question, Mr. Salman Khurshid said the 
withdrawal of Pakistan's resolution in Geneva was unconditional 
and there is no question of its postponement to the next session 
of the UN Human Rights Commission. The minister said there is 
no confusion, as the chairman himself made this clear at the 
Geneva meeting. 

</TEXT>

