<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Envoy Ross Meets With 'Arafat in Tunis </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC1403152894 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1440 GMT 14 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC1403152894 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tunis, 14 Mar (MENA)--PLO Chairman Yasir 'Arafat and 
Dennis Ross, the U.S. coordinator on the Middle East peace 
process, held a three-hour meeting in the presence of a number 
of Palestinian leaders. After the meeting, Ross said that the 
talks were useful and good and that he will meet with 'Arafat 
again this evening. Asked if the Palestinians will go to 
Washington to negotiate with the Israelis, Ross said that this 
issue has not yet been decided but consultations will be 
continued. 
  Yasir 'Abd-Rabbuh, head of the PLO Political Department, 
took 
part in the meeting and said that the talks with Ross were very 
useful and were characterized by frankness. He noted that the 
talks dealt with the details of the situation in the occupied 
territories and the need to provide security requirements for 
the Palestinian people so that political negotiations can be 
resumed. He said that the talks with Ross will resume this 
evening to continue discussion on the points that were not 
resolved during the meeting. 
  Members of the Palestinian and Israeli delegations declined 
to make any statements on the resolved issues or the points of 
disagreement. There are indications that during the meeting 
Ross failed to obtain 'Arafat's agreement to declare the PLO's 
return to the negotiating table with the Israelis and the 
resumption of the talks, which is the condition that the United 
States set on voting for the resolution submitted to the 
Security Council on the al-Ibrahimi Mosque massacre. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

